web.ws_protocol:
Path: GET /ws (one channel per KB / per app instance; in-process _Hub fan-out). Auth: when enabled, cookie `vouch_review_token` (primary, browser) or `?token=` query (CLI/desktop); constant-time compare; close code 4401 on mismatch. After accept the server immediately sends a greeting, then only ever pushes â any client->server text is received and discarded (the loop just keeps the socket open).

All frames are JSON text, sent with separators (",",":") (compact). Two frame families:

GREETING (once, on connect):
  {"type":"hello","kb":"<str store.root>"}

REVIEW frames (type=="refresh"), emitted by the mutation handler AFTER the write succeeds, via _notify(kind, **extra) -> hub.broadcast({"type":"refresh","view":kind,...extra}). Exact shapes seen:
  approve:     {"type":"refresh","view":"queue","action":"approve","proposal_id":"<id>","artifact_id":"<id|null>"}
  reject:      {"type":"refresh","view":"queue","action":"reject","proposal_id":"<id>"}
  contradict:  {"type":"refresh","view":"audit","action":"contradict","claim_id":"<id>"}
  The frame is a SIGNAL, not data â on receipt the client re-pulls the affected view (GET /api/pending for view==queue, /audit for view==audit). `view` is the only guaranteed field besides type; action/ids are advisory.

DUAL_SOLVE frames (type=="dual_solve"), shape from _frame(job,event,message):
  {"type":"dual_solve","job_id":"<hex>","event":"<event>","message":"<str>"}
  events: "progress" (message = one human-readable phase line, e.g. 'running claude (effort=high); this can take a few minutes', 'claude: produced a diff (N lines) in 2m03s'); "ready" (both engines done, message=''); "error" (message = exception text, from prepare-failure or finalize-failure); "done" (message='', after choose finalizes). The frame carries NO candidate data/diffs â the client must GET /dual-solve/job/{job_id} to read issue/candidates/diffs/proposed_ids after a 'ready' or 'done'.

Broadcast robustness: each send is wrapped in asyncio.wait_for with a 1.0s per-client timeout; a slow/dead client is dropped, never stalls the approve/reject handler that awaits the broadcast inline.
